The businessman then consulted with unspecified others and suggested adding a paragraph praising the powerful princes of Saudi Arabia and the UAE, the text messages show.
Barrack’s role in the proposed Saudi nuclear deal is now part of a federal investigation into illegal foreign lobbying, The New York Times reported on Sunday.
After Trump’s inauguration, Barrack’s “Marshall Plan” turned into an effort to build nuclear reactors in Saudi Arabia, according to the committee’s report.
In a September 2017 memo from Barrack, he said the firms would combine their funds with money from Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
Saudi Arabia still needs to sign a treaty with the U.S. before it can build nuclear power plants using U.S. technology.